---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const structuredData = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@graph": [
    {
      "@type": "WebSite",
      name: "mono-poly",
      url: "https://monopoly-repo.dev/",
      description:
        "Pragmatic code re-organization across repositories. Start with a monorepo, expand to polyrepo, consolidate back; without losing git history.",
    },
    {
      "@type": "SoftwareApplication",
      name: "monopoly",
      applicationCategory: "DeveloperApplication",
      operatingSystem: "macOS, Linux, Windows",
      url: "https://monopoly-repo.dev/cli/",
      description:
        "A small CLI for moving files or directories between git repositories while preserving full commit history. After you commit the move, git log --follow and git blame trace back to the original commits.",
      offers: {
        "@type": "Offer",
        price: "0",
        priceCurrency: "USD",
      },
      author: {
        "@type": "Person",
        name: "Itay Mendelawy",
        url: "https://itaymendel.dev",
      },
    },
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="mono-poly - Pragmatic code re-organization across repositories."
  description="Start with a monorepo, expand to polyrepo, consolidate back; without losing git history."
>
  <script
    type="application/ld+json"
    slot="head"
    is:inline
    set:html={JSON.stringify(structuredData)}
  />
  <section class="hero">
    <h1>Mono-Poly</h1>
    <p class="lede">Pragmatic code <i>re</i>-organization across repositories.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="intro">
    <p>
      <a href="/why">We've all been in monorepo vs polyrepo discussions</a>.
      They all share the same hidden assumption: that it's a one-and-done
      decision. But code structure should serve business demands and
      organization structure &mdash; and those change.
      <b>So never marry a specific method of code organization.</b>
    </p>
    <p>
      In most cases just start coding a new thing in an existing repo. As
      you learn more about business needs or the organization changes, consider moving it around.<br />
      <b>Break a monorepo, merge two repos, move code between repos. Whatever.</b>
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Git history</h2>
    <p>
      <i>"If I move code to another repo, I lose my git history"</i>. Well, no.
      With <a href="https://github.com/newren/git-filter-repo"
        ><code>git filter-repo</code></a
      > and <code>git merge --allow-unrelated-histories</code>, code carries its
      full commit history through every move (so <code>git blame</code> works). <a
        href="/cli">Use this CLI tool if you want</a
      >.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>AI</h2>
    <p>
      AI agents work better with focused codebases. Noise in codebases may cause
      AI to do things it shouldn't.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Business domains</h2>
    <p>
      New domains may appear, some will consolidate or flat out disappear. At times
      side-concerns become core. Repo boundaries should track those shifts, not
      freeze the state that was true 3 years ago.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Organization structure</h2>
    <p>
      <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conway%27s_law">Conway's Law</a> is real,
      and it impacts repo structure as well. Code location should match ownership.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Compromises</h2>
    <p>
      Moving code around means refactoring and introducing dependencies.
      It's not a bad thing if it's for sake of business needs or organization structure.
      Good engineering is all about making compromises.
    </p>
  </section>

</BaseLayout>
